Matternet right now
is working in Bhutan.

00:06:32.420 --> 00:06:36.870
In Bhutan, using drones to
transport food and medicines

00:06:36.870 --> 00:06:40.390
in a country that has almost
no roads or no infrastructure.

00:06:40.390 --> 00:06:43.130
Or other companies,
like Modern Meadow,

00:06:43.130 --> 00:06:46.060
that is working on
a cultured meat.

00:06:46.060 --> 00:06:47.970
Some people like to
call it in vitro meat.

00:06:47.970 --> 00:06:49.780
But we prefer cultured meat.

00:06:52.020 --> 00:06:53.372
So what is a singularity?

00:06:53.372 --> 00:06:55.580
Because I haven't told you
yet what is a singularity?

00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:57.510
Well, the father
of the singularity

00:06:57.510 --> 00:06:59.410
is right here, Ray Kurzweil.

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:02.120
And his famous book, "The
Singularity is Near,"

00:07:02.120 --> 00:07:07.060
is recommended by Bill Gates
as the best book in the world.

00:07:07.060 --> 00:07:09.060
Actually, I don't think
that that is right,

00:07:09.060 --> 00:07:11.560
because the best book
in the world is--

00:07:11.560 --> 00:07:12.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:12.100 --> 00:07:14.080
"The State of the
Future," that we

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:15.740
published with The
Millennium Project.

00:07:15.740 --> 00:07:18.254
But Bill Gates
hasn't read this yet.

00:07:19.580 --> 00:07:22.320
Nonetheless, why
is "The Singularity

00:07:22.320 --> 00:07:24.010
is Near" so important?

00:07:24.010 --> 00:07:27.620
Because Ray wrote,
about 10 years ago,

00:07:27.620 --> 00:07:29.300
about these incredible changes.

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:30.850
And forget about Moore's law.

00:07:30.850 --> 00:07:33.390
Moore's law is only
one little part

00:07:33.390 --> 00:07:37.300
of what Ray calls the law of
accelerating returns, which

00:07:37.300 --> 00:07:41.790
was beyond, before,
and after Moore's law.

00:07:41.790 --> 00:07:43.480
So we are living in
incredible times.

00:07:43.480 --> 00:07:47.370
If these trends continues,
in the next 20 to 30 years

00:07:47.370 --> 00:07:50.990
we will have computers that
have many more transistors

00:07:50.990 --> 00:07:52.870
that our brains have neurons.

00:07:53.910 --> 00:07:56.440
And I will talk a little
bit about that later.

00:07:56.440 --> 00:07:58.630
You probably remember
these old technologies,

00:07:58.630 --> 00:08:02.065
for some of you who
are old enough-- Ray.

00:08:04.420 --> 00:08:06.120
The punch cards,
the IBM punch cards,

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:08.210
these were used
40 two years ago.

00:08:08.210 --> 00:08:10.870
OK, this was 1 k memory, 1 k.

00:08:10.870 --> 00:08:14.790
This is 10 times
100, 1,000, 1 k.

00:08:14.790 --> 00:08:17.010
But these memories,
once you wrote on them,

00:08:17.010 --> 00:08:18.650
you couldn't erase.

00:08:18.650 --> 00:08:22.720
So electromagnetic
magnetic were invented.

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:25.760
This is 8 inches
and it is also 1 k.

00:08:25.760 --> 00:08:28.080
But this 1 k is
better than this 1 k

00:08:28.080 --> 00:08:29.550
because this you could erase.

00:08:29.550 --> 00:08:31.030
You could change.

00:08:31.030 --> 00:08:34.299
In Spanish, we say 1 k and 1 k.

00:08:34.299 --> 00:08:36.474
How much is 1 k plus 1 k?

00:08:36.474 --> 00:08:39.530
It is 1 kk, 1 kk.

00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:43.710
40 years ago, we
had 1 kk of memory.

00:08:43.710 --> 00:08:46.420
And then, obviously,
we moved to this.

00:08:46.420 --> 00:08:50.980
Some of you might
remember this, 512 kks.

00:08:50.980 --> 00:08:54.660
Then we moved to this, 1.4 mega.

00:08:54.660 --> 00:08:56.834
And I just came
back from Asia and I

00:08:56.834 --> 00:08:58.000
bought this beautiful thing.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:07.210
This has 128 gigabytes, $20--
128 gigabytes, $20 in China.

00:09:07.210 --> 00:09:09.320
So imagine what has
happened for 10 years?

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:13.560
We went from kk
to 128 gigabytes.

00:09:13.560 --> 00:09:16.040
What do you think is going to
happen in the next 30 years?

00:09:17.340 --> 00:09:19.370
You are going to remember
me, here, 30 years.

00:09:19.370 --> 00:09:21.150
And you will remember kk.

00:09:21.150 --> 00:09:22.370
But this will be kk.

00:09:23.450 --> 00:09:25.630
We are going to
have devices that

00:09:25.630 --> 00:09:29.280
have more transistors that we
have neurons in our brains,

00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:31.020
in the next few years.

00:09:31.020 --> 00:09:34.030
But anyway, I just wanted
to remind you of the history

00:09:34.030 --> 00:09:35.240
that we have gone through.

00:09:35.240 --> 00:09:36.860
This is happening
in all technologies,

00:09:36.860 --> 00:09:37.860
including biotechnology.

00:09:38.930 --> 00:09:41.360
At Singularity University,
the participants

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:43.505
in the summer programs get
their genome sequenced.

00:09:44.600 --> 00:09:46.746
There are maybe
devices like this.

00:09:46.746 --> 00:09:49.540
This is a gene chip
to sequence a genome.

00:09:49.540 --> 00:09:51.995
And it allows you
to know what you

00:09:51.995 --> 00:09:55.150
are made of, what
diseases you will have.

00:09:55.150 --> 00:09:56.860
For example, what
is the probability

00:09:56.860 --> 00:10:00.540
that I will psoriasis,
diabetes, prostate cancer,

00:10:00.540 --> 00:10:03.530
and many other things I don't
want to show-- Alzheimer's,

00:10:03.530 --> 00:10:05.560
Parkinson, and so on?

00:10:05.560 --> 00:10:09.930
One of my personal traits-- the
color of my eyes-- all of this

00:10:09.930 --> 00:10:11.640
is written in our genes.

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:14.450
So soon-- I guess many of
you have already done this

00:10:14.450 --> 00:10:18.170
because this has existed for
about almost 10 years, some

00:10:18.170 --> 00:10:19.200
of these technologies.

00:10:19.200 --> 00:10:21.100
But soon, all of
us will have this.

00:10:21.100 --> 00:10:23.180
And we'll understand
this because we don't yet

00:10:23.180 --> 00:10:24.790
understand the genome.

00:10:24.790 --> 00:10:28.450
And soon you will know what
is the color of your eyes,

00:10:28.450 --> 00:10:29.660
if you didn't know it.

00:10:29.660 --> 00:10:34.420
And what you will die of--
so that you do not die of it.

00:10:34.420 --> 00:10:34.920
OK.

00:10:34.920 --> 00:10:38.050
Because the beautiful is
that medicine will change.

00:10:38.050 --> 00:10:40.410
Medicine now is about art.

00:10:40.410 --> 00:10:42.310
And soon it will
be a good science.

00:10:42.310 --> 00:10:45.190
Another thing you
will discover, if you

00:10:45.190 --> 00:10:50.720
have done the 23andMe or other
similar mechanism like this,

00:10:50.720 --> 00:10:53.430
is, for example, where
do you come from?

00:10:53.430 --> 00:10:54.950
Where did your
ancestors come from?

00:10:54.950 --> 00:10:58.980
And this is my parents,
my father 500 years ago.

00:10:58.980 --> 00:11:02.400
You can see he comes from
Spain, all the way to Asia,

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:03.690
to Mongolia.

00:11:03.690 --> 00:11:06.320
And you will see famous
people related to my father,

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:08.200
like Genghis Khan.

00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:09.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:09.040 --> 00:11:13.650
Now, I will show you my maternal
line, also 500 years ago.

00:11:13.650 --> 00:11:16.940
And so she comes also from
Spain, all the way to Siberia.

00:11:16.940 --> 00:11:19.465
And famous people related to
my mother, Marie Antoinette.

00:11:20.600 --> 00:11:23.830
So I come from a very
aristocratic family,

00:11:23.830 --> 00:11:25.730
between Genghis Khan
and Marie Antoinette.

00:11:27.380 --> 00:11:33.350
With this, you will be able to
construct your geological tree.

00:11:33.350 --> 00:11:35.040
And you would know
for the first time

00:11:35.040 --> 00:11:37.120
if your father is
really your father.

00:11:38.515 --> 00:11:39.890
But more interesting
than looking

00:11:39.890 --> 00:11:42.980
backwards is looking forwards.

00:11:42.980 --> 00:11:46.370
And in the future, we
will design our children.

00:11:46.370 --> 00:11:48.150
This is an experiment
that I did with one

00:11:48.150 --> 00:11:50.810
of my students, Sharon James.

00:11:50.810 --> 00:11:53.230
This is a theoretical
experiment, OK,

00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:55.580
to find out how our
children could be.

00:11:55.580 --> 00:11:58.280
What is the probability
for different conditions,

00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:00.430
different traits,
different diseases?

00:12:00.430 --> 00:12:03.210
And then pick those that you
want or that you do not want.

00:12:04.470 --> 00:12:07.610
Obviously, this was incredibly
expensive at the beginning.

00:12:07.610 --> 00:12:11.650
The first genome began
to be sequenced in 1990.

00:12:11.650 --> 00:12:14.050
The Human Genome
Project began in 1990

00:12:14.050 --> 00:12:16.540
and it finished in 2003.

00:12:16.540 --> 00:12:18.510
It took 13 years.

00:12:18.510 --> 00:12:21.790
And it cost the US
government $1 billion,

00:12:21.790 --> 00:12:25.680
plus $2 other billion from other
governments, Europe, Japan,

00:12:25.680 --> 00:12:26.630
and so on.

00:12:26.630 --> 00:12:30.230
$3 billion, 13
years, one genome.

00:12:30.230 --> 00:12:34.380
Today, you can sequence
the full genome

00:12:34.380 --> 00:12:37.880
for slightly over $1,000 today.

00:12:37.880 --> 00:12:40.966
And if you do the partial
sequence, like 23andMe,

00:12:40.966 --> 00:12:41.466
it is $99.

00:12:43.530 --> 00:12:47.450
We expect that by 2025, at
the latest, it will cost $10.

00:12:48.930 --> 00:12:51.730
And it will take only
one minute to do.

00:12:51.730 --> 00:12:53.970
If you remember
this, remember kk?

00:12:55.140 --> 00:12:57.080
Well, what is happening
in biotechnology

00:12:57.080 --> 00:13:01.840
is more incredible, from $1
billion to $10; from 13 years,

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:03.280
to one minute.

00:13:03.280 --> 00:13:04.281
This is incredible.

00:13:04.281 --> 00:13:06.030
And this is happening
in all technologies.

00:13:07.590 --> 00:13:09.880
Also, even in economics.

00:13:09.880 --> 00:13:12.480
If we look at how
development is changing,

00:13:12.480 --> 00:13:15.180
countries are growing
faster and faster.

00:13:15.180 --> 00:13:17.640
The first nation that
doubled its income per capita

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:20.790
was the United Kingdom, during
the Industrial Revolution.

00:13:20.790 --> 00:13:24.930
And it took the UK
between 1780 and 1838.

00:13:24.930 --> 00:13:28.990
That is 58 years to be the
first nation in human history

00:13:28.990 --> 00:13:31.030
that doubled its
income per capita.

00:13:31.030 --> 00:13:33.710
Today, China is doing
that every seven years.

00:13:33.710 --> 00:13:36.180
This is absolutely incredible.

00:13:36.180 --> 00:13:38.270
If you look at this
throughout the centuries,

00:13:38.270 --> 00:13:40.880
the last millennium,
humanity didn't really

00:13:40.880 --> 00:13:43.640
grow until the beginning of
the Industrial Revolution,

00:13:43.640 --> 00:13:45.790
late in the 18th century.

00:13:45.790 --> 00:13:49.020
By the 19th century,
the GDP per capita,

00:13:49.020 --> 00:13:52.480
cumulative of the planet,
grew 100% in the century.

00:13:52.480 --> 00:13:56.380
Last century, in the 20th
century, it grew almost 400%.

00:13:56.380 --> 00:13:58.930
If this rate continues,
and I believe it will,

00:13:58.930 --> 00:14:04.050
we'll probably grow 2000%,
3000%, 4000% this century.

00:14:04.050 --> 00:14:07.160
We have seen nothing yet
of what is going to happen.

00:14:07.160 --> 00:14:10.070
Additionally, the population is
finally becoming more stable,

00:14:10.070 --> 00:14:12.650
if we look long term,
from the 18th century.

00:14:12.650 --> 00:14:16.180
And look, that this
is a linear scale.

00:14:16.180 --> 00:14:20.570
Now, I want to show you the
same change for GDP per capita.

00:14:20.570 --> 00:14:23.356
Because the GDP, the income,
is growing exponentially.

00:14:25.410 --> 00:14:30.180
From the 18th century, when
humanity had a relatively low

00:14:30.180 --> 00:14:34.360
income-- all of humanity was
around $1,000 per capita,

00:14:34.360 --> 00:14:38.000
per year, that was until
the Industrial Revolution--

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:39.290
it began growing.

00:14:39.290 --> 00:14:40.870
And then it reached $10,000.

00:14:40.870 --> 00:14:44.150
Soon it will reach $100,000.

00:14:44.150 --> 00:14:46.415
And look that there is
the catching up affect

00:14:46.415 --> 00:14:48.800
of the poorer countries
growing faster.

00:14:48.800 --> 00:14:51.085
So we are truly living
in incredible times.

00:14:52.300 --> 00:14:55.300
So things are changing
exponentially faster, becoming

00:14:55.300 --> 00:14:57.920
smaller, cheaper, and better.

00:14:57.920 --> 00:15:01.390
This is an example that Peter
Diamandis, the co-founder

00:15:01.390 --> 00:15:03.970
of Singularity University,
likes to talk about--

00:15:03.970 --> 00:15:09.360
and Ray-- about comparing
linear and exponential steps.

00:15:09.360 --> 00:15:15.140
If you give 30 linear steps, you
advanced 30 meters, 1, 2, 3, 4,

00:15:15.140 --> 00:15:16.550
5, 6, 7.

00:15:16.550 --> 00:15:20.270
If you take exponential
steps, after 30 steps,

00:15:20.270 --> 00:15:24.000
you go around the
planet 26 times.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.560
And this is something
that we cannot comprehend.

00:15:26.560 --> 00:15:31.230
Our brains cannot understand
easily exponential change.

00:15:31.230 --> 00:15:33.205
But technology is
changing exponentially.

