A few years ago-- a few years
ago, six, seven years ago,

00:18:26.570 --> 00:18:30.850
I went to visit Sir Arthur
C. Clarke, before he died,

00:18:30.850 --> 00:18:32.330
in Sri Lanka.

00:18:32.330 --> 00:18:36.060
And he's very famous
among futurists.

00:18:37.266 --> 00:18:38.890
Sir Arthur C. Clarke,
he's very famous,

00:18:38.890 --> 00:18:41.200
not just because of "A
Space Odyssey 2001."

00:18:41.200 --> 00:18:44.655
He's very famous because of
the three laws of the future.

00:18:47.550 --> 00:18:48.710
I'll read them to you.

00:18:48.710 --> 00:18:51.540
The first law-- when a
distinguished, famous scientist

00:18:51.540 --> 00:18:54.400
says that something is
possible, he's probably right.

00:18:54.400 --> 00:18:56.250
But when he says
it is impossible,

00:18:56.250 --> 00:18:58.360
he is probably wrong.

00:18:58.360 --> 00:19:01.210
Second law of the future--
the only way of discovering

00:19:01.210 --> 00:19:03.779
the limits of the
possible is to venture

00:19:03.779 --> 00:19:05.320
pass the limits,
into the impossible.

00:19:06.700 --> 00:19:08.660
And the third law--
any sufficiently

00:19:08.660 --> 00:19:12.420
advanced technology is
indistinguishable from magic.

00:19:12.420 --> 00:19:14.670
So now I am going
to talk about magic.

00:19:14.670 --> 00:19:17.780
Because the technologies of
the future have to be magical.

00:19:17.780 --> 00:19:19.380
And if they don't
look like magic,

00:19:19.380 --> 00:19:20.838
it's because they
are not advanced.

00:19:22.120 --> 00:19:27.730
30 years ago, we just began
using personal computers.

00:19:27.730 --> 00:19:31.240
Actually, I remember when I
did my master's thesis at MIT.

00:19:31.240 --> 00:19:37.590
I actually used a prehistoric
technology called "typewriter"

00:19:37.590 --> 00:19:39.480
for my first thesis at MIT.

00:19:39.480 --> 00:19:43.310
Imagine a typewriter, that
prehistoric technology.

00:19:43.310 --> 00:19:46.740
20 years ago, mobile telephone
were becoming popular.

00:19:46.740 --> 00:19:51.210
10 years ago, Google was still
growing up, a small start-up.

00:19:51.210 --> 00:19:54.760
So what is going to happen
in the next 10, 20, 30 years?

00:19:54.760 --> 00:19:57.790
We are going to have
incredible technologies.

00:19:57.790 --> 00:20:00.085
One of them is the
control of aging.

00:20:01.520 --> 00:20:03.450
Actually, we have
some of the faculty

00:20:03.450 --> 00:20:06.090
of Singularity University
that say that aging

00:20:06.090 --> 00:20:09.930
is a disease, but
a curable disease.

00:20:09.930 --> 00:20:13.650
And we will cure disease within
in the next 20 to 30 years.

00:20:13.650 --> 00:20:17.630
In fact, I believe we are going
to see physical mortality soon,

00:20:17.630 --> 00:20:20.230
what I call the death of death.

00:20:21.830 --> 00:20:25.310
Actually to put
this into reference,

00:20:25.310 --> 00:20:28.560
we already have cells
which are immortal,

00:20:28.560 --> 00:20:30.500
which are the germinal cells.

00:20:30.500 --> 00:20:32.927
Germinal cells do not age.

00:20:32.927 --> 00:20:35.010
That doesn't mean that
they are actually immortal.

00:20:35.010 --> 00:20:37.320
Because if someone
kills them, they die.

00:20:37.320 --> 00:20:38.900
But they do not age.

00:20:38.900 --> 00:20:40.070
The same as bacteria.

00:20:40.070 --> 00:20:43.322
Bacteria do not age.

00:20:43.322 --> 00:20:44.530
Again, they are not immortal.

00:20:44.530 --> 00:20:45.696
You might kill the bacteria.

00:20:45.696 --> 00:20:48.517
But they do not age, which
is the important concept.

00:20:48.517 --> 00:20:50.100
And then we have
another type of cells

00:20:50.100 --> 00:20:53.940
which are pretty bad, which
are the cancer cells, that also

00:20:53.940 --> 00:20:57.710
discover how to become immortal,
or at least how not to age.

00:20:57.710 --> 00:20:59.640
So we know this is
possible because we

00:20:59.640 --> 00:21:03.184
have good cells that not age
and bad cells that do not age.

00:21:03.184 --> 00:21:04.850
Now, there are many
companies and groups

00:21:04.850 --> 00:21:06.980
