And we will have
incredible, clean cities

00:25:34.690 --> 00:25:35.940
which are very advanced.

00:25:35.940 --> 00:25:38.520
The second technology,
biotechnology.

00:25:38.520 --> 00:25:42.850
Which I like to describe
as living nanotechnology--

00:25:42.850 --> 00:25:44.575
nanotechnology, but alive.

00:25:46.890 --> 00:25:49.390
Many experiments have been
done in the last few years.

00:25:49.390 --> 00:25:51.150
10 years ago, a
Taiwanese company

00:25:51.150 --> 00:25:53.350
began creating these
glowfish, which

00:25:53.350 --> 00:25:58.200
are transgenic fish-- the zebra
fish with the fluorescent gene

00:25:58.200 --> 00:26:00.020
of the Medusa from
the Caribbean.

00:26:00.020 --> 00:26:03.700
And you can have these zebra
fish in five different colors,

00:26:03.700 --> 00:26:04.470
really beautiful.

00:26:05.720 --> 00:26:09.940
Actually last year-- or two
years ago-- one of our students

00:26:09.940 --> 00:26:12.170
at Singularity
University created

00:26:12.170 --> 00:26:14.770
this company, Glowing Plants.

00:26:16.050 --> 00:26:20.100
Which is a plant that has also
the gene of bioluminescence

00:26:20.100 --> 00:26:21.660
from the firefly.

00:26:21.660 --> 00:26:25.930
He was looking for $65,000.

00:26:25.930 --> 00:26:30.910
And at the end of the process,
he had $300,000, $400,000.

00:26:30.910 --> 00:26:33.810
He almost got half
a million dollars

00:26:33.810 --> 00:26:35.200
for these glowing plants.

00:26:35.200 --> 00:26:35.700
OK.

00:26:35.700 --> 00:26:39.160
Obviously, he advertised they
might be marijuana plants.

00:26:39.160 --> 00:26:41.870
And some people like
growing marijuana.

00:26:41.870 --> 00:26:43.456
But actually--

00:26:43.456 --> 00:26:44.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:44.860 --> 00:26:47.100
--actually, these
are tomato plants.

00:26:47.100 --> 00:26:48.940
Some people like tomato too.

00:26:48.940 --> 00:26:51.530
Anyway, this is incredible,
one of the students

00:26:51.530 --> 00:26:53.630
of Singularity University
working on that.

00:26:53.630 --> 00:26:58.440
Also, one of our faculty at
Singularity University, Stewart

00:26:58.440 --> 00:27:01.240
Brand, he's working
on de-extinction,

00:27:01.240 --> 00:27:04.720
to bring back the
species that have died,

00:27:04.720 --> 00:27:05.810
that have disappeared.

00:27:05.810 --> 00:27:09.270
One of the easiest cases
actually are the mammoth.

00:27:09.270 --> 00:27:12.280
There are many frozen
mammoths in Siberia.

00:27:12.280 --> 00:27:14.290
So many that the
Russian government

00:27:14.290 --> 00:27:16.180
is working with
several scientists

00:27:16.180 --> 00:27:18.610
from the USA, from
Japan, and Korea,

00:27:18.610 --> 00:27:20.580
to bring them back to life.

00:27:20.580 --> 00:27:23.540
And they even created
a Pleistocene park.

00:27:23.540 --> 00:27:26.730
Not Jurassic Park,
but a Pleistocene park

00:27:26.730 --> 00:27:28.340
in northern Siberia.

00:27:28.340 --> 00:27:31.200
So probably we will have
mammoths back to life

00:27:31.200 --> 00:27:32.605
in the next few
years, in Russia.

00:27:33.980 --> 00:27:36.780
And cloning, cloning is
an important technology.

00:27:36.780 --> 00:27:38.900
But not for reproduction.

00:27:38.900 --> 00:27:40.890
For reproduction is
better the typical system.

00:27:42.370 --> 00:27:44.830
Cloning will be used,
not for reproduction,

00:27:44.830 --> 00:27:49.600
but for therapeutic reasons, to
create organs, to fix organs.

00:27:49.600 --> 00:27:51.390
And this is a very
interesting technology.

00:27:51.390 --> 00:27:55.320
That in Singapore, Lee Kuan
Yew, the father of Singapore,

00:27:55.320 --> 00:27:58.540
created a city called
Biopolis, where

00:27:58.540 --> 00:28:00.240
they are doing all
kinds of experiments

00:28:00.240 --> 00:28:03.570
on biotechnology and cloning.

00:28:03.570 --> 00:28:06.120
But many other countries
are doing that, like Russia.

00:28:06.120 --> 00:28:08.590
And the problem with
Russia is you never

00:28:08.590 --> 00:28:10.090
know what the
Russians are thinking.

00:28:10.090 --> 00:28:10.800
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:10.800 --> 00:28:13.470
So you have to be careful
about the Russians

00:28:13.470 --> 00:28:14.455
and cloning in Russia.

00:28:15.620 --> 00:28:18.940
But another incredible country
working on this is India.

00:28:18.940 --> 00:28:19.830
And I love India.

00:28:19.830 --> 00:28:21.690
I have been many times to India.

00:28:21.690 --> 00:28:25.460
And if you know the Indian
gods, they are very strange.

00:28:25.460 --> 00:28:28.690
They have gods that
have three heads, gods

00:28:28.690 --> 00:28:30.470
that have eight arms.

00:28:30.470 --> 00:28:34.600
However, think how useful it
could be to have three heads?

00:28:34.600 --> 00:28:37.740
One head is working,
one head is having fun,

00:28:37.740 --> 00:28:41.510
and the third head is
sleeping, all at the same time.

00:28:43.180 --> 00:28:45.460
Or having eight arms--
wouldn't this be wonderful?

00:28:46.920 --> 00:28:48.140
I know that you laugh.

00:28:48.140 --> 00:28:50.967
But if you come from
India, this is normal

00:28:50.967 --> 00:28:53.050
because your gods have
three heads and eight arms.

00:28:54.280 --> 00:28:58.270
So I want you to come out
of your Western model,

00:28:58.270 --> 00:29:01.580
for some of you, and to
think about other religions.

00:29:01.580 --> 00:29:03.870
Because also in India,
they believe in rebirth.

00:29:03.870 --> 00:29:05.500
They believe in reincarnation.

00:29:05.500 --> 00:29:09.660
And what is the closest thing
in biology to reincarnation,

00:29:09.660 --> 00:29:10.740
cloning.

00:29:10.740 --> 00:29:14.280
OK, so India is advancing very
fast on cloning technologies.

00:29:15.350 --> 00:29:17.890
And now let me tell you the
first of the two numbers

00:29:17.890 --> 00:29:19.810
that I want you
to memorize, which

00:29:19.810 --> 00:29:22.610
is the complexity of
the human hardware.

00:29:22.610 --> 00:29:24.310
And later I will tell
you the complexity

00:29:24.310 --> 00:29:25.280
of the human software.

00:29:27.180 --> 00:29:30.330
Scientists, 10 years ago,
created an artificial virus.

00:29:30.330 --> 00:29:33.680
But a virus is very
small, has very few genes,

00:29:33.680 --> 00:29:36.350
and a small number of
base pairs of nucleotides.

00:29:36.350 --> 00:29:41.190
If you remember biology, A
goes with T and C goes with--

00:29:41.190 --> 00:29:41.690
AUDIENCE: G.

00:29:41.690 --> 00:29:43.310
JOSE CORDEIRO: --G.

00:29:43.310 --> 00:29:47.480
So basically, an artificial
virus was created 10 years ago.

00:29:47.480 --> 00:29:50.030
Two years ago, another
scientist-- actually,

00:29:50.030 --> 00:29:53.395
Craig Venter-- created
an artificial bacteria.

00:29:54.750 --> 00:29:57.230
But bacteria are
obviously bigger.

00:29:57.230 --> 00:30:01.620
And in order to prove that
he created the bacteria,

00:30:01.620 --> 00:30:04.300
the scientists
even put the email

00:30:04.300 --> 00:30:06.115
of the team that
created the bacteria.

00:30:08.330 --> 00:30:10.530
But still, a bacteria is small.

00:30:10.530 --> 00:30:13.910
However, how long will it take
until we can create something

00:30:13.910 --> 00:30:15.380
like a human being?

00:30:15.380 --> 00:30:17.560
And that is number one.

00:30:17.560 --> 00:30:19.970
3 gigabytes, that
is the complexity

00:30:19.970 --> 00:30:22.900
of the human
hardware, 3 gigabytes.

00:30:22.900 --> 00:30:24.740
Even the most
complex people here

00:30:24.740 --> 00:30:26.660
has no more than 3 gigabytes.

00:30:26.660 --> 00:30:29.080
Even Ray has only 3 gigabytes.

00:30:29.080 --> 00:30:29.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:29.580 --> 00:30:31.650
Here, I have a pen drive--

00:30:31.650 --> 00:30:33.830
RAY KURTZWEIL: There's
massive redundancy in that.

00:30:33.830 --> 00:30:34.890
JOSE CORDEIRO: On top.

00:30:34.890 --> 00:30:35.445
Thank you.

00:30:35.445 --> 00:30:38.210
RAY KURTZWEIL: And like
ALUs are [INAUDIBLE],

00:30:38.210 --> 00:30:39.797
like a thousand times.

00:30:39.797 --> 00:30:40.880
JOSE CORDEIRO: Absolutely.

00:30:40.880 --> 00:30:41.544
RAY KURTZWEIL:
The natural amount

00:30:41.544 --> 00:30:43.868
of data, if you just
compress out the redundancy,

00:30:43.868 --> 00:30:46.109
is about 50 million bytes.

00:30:46.109 --> 00:30:47.900
JOSE CORDEIRO: So you
see how small we are?

00:30:49.360 --> 00:30:52.090
And this pen drive
has 128 gigabytes.

00:30:52.090 --> 00:30:55.340
So how many people
can I fit here?

00:30:55.340 --> 00:30:58.120
Divide 128 gigabytes
by 3 gigabytes

00:30:58.120 --> 00:31:01.300
and add the redundancy
factor that Ray mentioned.

00:31:01.300 --> 00:31:06.850
And here you can fit 42
people and a little cat.

00:31:06.850 --> 00:31:08.340
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:08.340 --> 00:31:08.840
OK.

00:31:08.840 --> 00:31:13.320
Now I will move into the
complexity of the processing

00:31:13.320 --> 00:31:14.030
software.

00:31:14.030 --> 00:31:18.240
For that, we wanted to-- well,
again, remember, we humans,

00:31:18.240 --> 00:31:22.960
we are basically four
letters, A, T, C, G.

00:31:22.960 --> 00:31:24.710
The third technology,
info technology.

00:31:26.140 --> 00:31:29.920
According to the advances in
computers and the processing

00:31:29.920 --> 00:31:32.850
power, we are basically
reaching the complexity

00:31:32.850 --> 00:31:34.400
of a spider, a lizard.

00:31:34.400 --> 00:31:36.220
And then in 20,
30, years, we will

00:31:36.220 --> 00:31:39.350
reach the complexity of
a monkey, of a human.

00:31:39.350 --> 00:31:40.960
And everything
will be connected,

00:31:40.960 --> 00:31:42.920
just like in
telecommunications, becoming

00:31:42.920 --> 00:31:44.750
smaller and more powerful.

00:31:44.750 --> 00:31:47.470
And soon we will get
into the fifth generation

00:31:47.470 --> 00:31:48.820
of telecommunications.

00:31:48.820 --> 00:31:53.530
So much, that I was traveling
in Scandinavia a few months ago

00:31:53.530 --> 00:31:56.480
and I saw this advertisement
about telecommunications,

00:31:56.480 --> 00:31:59.710
where they say that the children
will actually be born already

00:31:59.710 --> 00:32:01.000
with internet connected.

00:32:02.240 --> 00:32:05.290
And the first thing they will
ask is for more bandwidth.

00:32:05.290 --> 00:32:07.010
They need more bandwidth.

00:32:07.010 --> 00:32:10.730
Because we are going to connect
everybody with everybody.

00:32:10.730 --> 00:32:15.640
We will probably create a
global brain, a global network,

00:32:15.640 --> 00:32:18.940
into what is called "the
internet of things."

00:32:18.940 --> 00:32:22.120
Everything will be
connected with everything,

00:32:22.120 --> 00:32:24.100
the internet of things.

00:32:24.100 --> 00:32:28.470
And people, computers,
cars-- especially

00:32:28.470 --> 00:32:31.280
if they drive themselves,
the self-driving cars.

00:32:31.280 --> 00:32:33.270
Also BMW.

00:32:33.270 --> 00:32:39.950
And now, that by 2025, all other
cars will be fully automatic,

00:32:39.950 --> 00:32:41.310
fully self-driving cars.

00:32:41.310 --> 00:32:42.790
They don't want humans.

00:32:42.790 --> 00:32:43.930
We are very bad driving.

00:32:45.160 --> 00:32:47.800
So they don't want
humans driving cars.

00:32:47.800 --> 00:32:51.220
And we will connect
ourselves with internet

00:32:51.220 --> 00:32:52.340
in different ways.

00:32:52.340 --> 00:32:54.390
Google Glass is one
of those new ways.

00:32:54.390 --> 00:32:57.980
Internet to our eyes and our
eyes to internet, for example.

00:32:57.980 --> 00:32:59.720
But what I find
truly fascinating

00:32:59.720 --> 00:33:04.570
was the announcement
made in April, last year,

00:33:04.570 --> 00:33:08.680
by Eric Schmidt, about
connecting the whole planet

00:33:08.680 --> 00:33:10.600
with free internet.

00:33:10.600 --> 00:33:11.670
This is beautiful.

00:33:11.670 --> 00:33:13.740
This will change the world.

00:33:13.740 --> 00:33:14.940
It will change the world.

00:33:14.940 --> 00:33:16.606
But then obviously,
other companies they

00:33:16.606 --> 00:33:17.770
will stay behind.

00:33:17.770 --> 00:33:20.540
And Mark Zuckerberg
announced a few months later

00:33:20.540 --> 00:33:22.910
that Facebook had a
different program.

00:33:22.910 --> 00:33:25.780
But also with the
objective, by 2020,

00:33:25.780 --> 00:33:29.090
to connect the whole planet,
in the middle of the Sahara,

00:33:29.090 --> 00:33:32.150
in the middle of the Pacific
Ocean, in the North Pole.

00:33:32.150 --> 00:33:37.770
But later still, another group,
called Outernet, as opposed

00:33:37.770 --> 00:33:39.285
to internet,
Outernet, because they

00:33:39.285 --> 00:33:40.660
are working with
microsatellites.

00:33:41.940 --> 00:33:44.410
I don't know if their
microsatellites,

00:33:44.410 --> 00:33:47.660
or if the drones, or if
the balloons will win.

00:33:47.660 --> 00:33:52.210
What I do know is
that before 2020, we

00:33:52.210 --> 00:33:55.080
will have free internet
in the whole planet,

00:33:55.080 --> 00:33:56.270
in the whole planet.

00:33:56.270 --> 00:33:58.880
This is the most
incredible thing

00:33:58.880 --> 00:34:01.201
to democratize knowledge,
to democratize access

00:34:01.201 --> 00:34:01.825
to information.

00:34:03.230 --> 00:34:06.120
And artificial intelligence
gave us some programs.

00:34:06.120 --> 00:34:11.639
And you are all familiar with
IBM's Watson, that in 2011 beat

00:34:11.639 --> 00:34:14.960
the two experts in the
game, Ken and Brad.

00:34:14.960 --> 00:34:17.380
Actually, Ken was
normally so good

00:34:17.380 --> 00:34:20.340
at playing Jeopardy
that he even wrote

00:34:20.340 --> 00:34:22.969
a book about how to win
at the game Jeopardy.

00:34:24.060 --> 00:34:26.170
And do you know what Watson did?

00:34:26.170 --> 00:34:27.796
Watson read the book.

00:34:27.796 --> 00:34:28.690
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:28.690 --> 00:34:30.940
But Watson not only
read that book,

00:34:30.940 --> 00:34:35.389
Watson was born with
Wikipedia in its head.

00:34:35.389 --> 00:34:39.040
How many of you have
Wikipedia in your brains,

00:34:39.040 --> 00:34:41.370
or even 1% of it?

00:34:41.370 --> 00:34:44.850
And do you even remember
1% of what you have read?

00:34:44.850 --> 00:34:46.679
Well, Watson remembers it all.

00:34:47.909 --> 00:34:49.750
Now, obviously, it
was very expensive.

00:34:49.750 --> 00:34:53.429
It was over $40 million
TO develop Watson.

00:34:53.429 --> 00:34:57.095
Many scientists work during
four years, or a bit longer.

00:34:58.460 --> 00:35:02.030
But, soon, it would
probably be free.

00:35:02.030 --> 00:35:05.440
It will be a free application,
like it happened before

00:35:05.440 --> 00:35:13.450
with Deep Blue, when in 1997,
beat the world chess champion,

00:35:13.450 --> 00:35:14.760
Garry Kasparov.

00:35:14.760 --> 00:35:17.770
That computer actually
was much more expensive.

00:35:17.770 --> 00:35:20.950
That computer was
over $100 million.

00:35:20.950 --> 00:35:23.880
And it took IBM over 10 years.

00:35:23.880 --> 00:35:26.880
Obviously, we had bad
technology 20 years ago,

00:35:26.880 --> 00:35:28.640
compared to what we have today.

00:35:28.640 --> 00:35:30.920
Do you know how
much is that today?

00:35:30.920 --> 00:35:34.590
You can buy the descendant
of Deep Blue for free.

00:35:35.630 --> 00:35:39.400
You can get descendants of
Deep Blue free in internet.

00:35:39.400 --> 00:35:42.200
And no human can
beat those programs.

00:35:42.200 --> 00:35:44.150
So anyway, one of the
first applications,

00:35:44.150 --> 00:35:48.150
as you probably know,
of IBM, is Dr. Watson.

00:35:48.150 --> 00:35:51.870
In order to become a
good medical doctor

00:35:51.870 --> 00:35:54.070
it will know all the
books of medicine,

00:35:54.070 --> 00:35:56.160
all the journals of medicine.

00:35:56.160 --> 00:35:59.930
All the personal histories of
the patients who allow that.

00:35:59.930 --> 00:36:03.860
No human can have access or
process all that information.

00:36:03.860 --> 00:36:06.670
So finally, medicine
will be good.

00:36:06.670 --> 00:36:10.080
Instead of bad, as it is now,
it will be a good science.

00:36:10.080 --> 00:36:13.310
And so we arrive at the
last and final technology,

00:36:13.310 --> 00:36:17.140
which is the most
interesting-- cognitive

00:36:17.140 --> 00:36:20.410
technology,
neuroscience, the brain.

00:36:20.410 --> 00:36:22.330
The brain is very
important because it

00:36:22.330 --> 00:36:25.880
is the most complex
organ in the human body.

00:36:25.880 --> 00:36:28.000
And it is basically
the only organ

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:32.400
that we have not been able to
reproduce artificially yet.

00:36:32.400 --> 00:36:35.620
We have been able to do almost
anything, artificial eyes,

00:36:35.620 --> 00:36:39.190
artificial pancreas, artificial
lungs, artificial heart,

00:36:39.190 --> 00:36:41.520
everything except for the brain.

00:36:41.520 --> 00:36:42.280
Why?

00:36:42.280 --> 00:36:45.040
Because the brain is
the most complex organ.

00:36:45.040 --> 00:36:49.180
Not only that, it is the
most complex structure

00:36:49.180 --> 00:36:50.615
in the known universe.

00:36:51.930 --> 00:36:55.210
Maybe tomorrow, we have a
Martian, who has a bigger brain

00:36:55.210 --> 00:36:56.360
that we humans.

00:36:56.360 --> 00:36:58.500
But until that time,
there is nothing

00:36:58.500 --> 00:37:01.215
that we know of more complex
than the human brain.

00:37:02.300 --> 00:37:03.370
And you know what?

00:37:03.370 --> 00:37:05.215
The brain is not that complex.

00:37:05.215 --> 00:37:06.620
And in the next
few years, we are

00:37:06.620 --> 00:37:09.200
going to decipher
the brain, which

00:37:09.200 --> 00:37:12.390
is the final frontier
in terms of complexity.

00:37:12.390 --> 00:37:14.360
But we will go beyond the brain.

00:37:14.360 --> 00:37:19.590
For that, you have to read Ray's
book, "How to Create a Mind."

00:37:19.590 --> 00:37:21.250
He explains a lot about that.

00:37:21.250 --> 00:37:23.615
And now the book
is in Spanish, it

00:37:23.615 --> 00:37:26.860
is in German, and in
many other languages.

00:37:26.860 --> 00:37:30.410
And it is recommended
by my colleague

00:37:30.410 --> 00:37:33.640
from Venezuela, who is the
president of MIT, Rafael Reif,

00:37:33.640 --> 00:37:36.640
as one of the best
books there is

00:37:36.640 --> 00:37:39.740
to understand how the
mind, the brain work.

00:37:39.740 --> 00:37:41.620
And how did the brain evolve?

00:37:41.620 --> 00:37:44.100
We understand today
that the brain

00:37:44.100 --> 00:37:46.520
has been changing through ages.

00:37:46.520 --> 00:37:49.910
In fact, in Japan, they have
the Riken Brain Institute,

00:37:49.910 --> 00:37:53.090
where they have followed the
evolution, biological evolution

00:37:53.090 --> 00:37:56.380
of the brain and how the
brain can continue evolving,

00:37:56.380 --> 00:37:57.510
can continue changing.

00:37:59.010 --> 00:38:03.500
So also in terms of the genome,
let me tell you once all of you

00:38:03.500 --> 00:38:06.240
sequence your genome,
you will realize

00:38:06.240 --> 00:38:08.900
that we are 99%
equal to a monkey.

00:38:10.670 --> 00:38:12.220
We are very close to a monkey.

00:38:13.980 --> 00:38:16.805
And we are about 90%
equal to a mouse.

00:38:18.050 --> 00:38:20.110
So actually we are very similar.

00:38:20.110 --> 00:38:22.500
So if we are only
1% above-- to put

00:38:22.500 --> 00:38:25.930
it that way-- above a
monkey, or 10% above a mouse,

00:38:25.930 --> 00:38:31.460
can you imagine 1% above a
human, or 10% above a human,

00:38:31.460 --> 00:38:33.750
or 100% above a human?

00:38:33.750 --> 00:38:35.700
So all these things,
we are going to see.

00:38:35.700 --> 00:38:38.990
Anywhere, in Japan they are
working on this brain research

00:38:38.990 --> 00:38:39.920
institute.

00:38:39.920 --> 00:38:43.310
And they originally had
a plan for the year 2018

00:38:43.310 --> 00:38:44.960
to create artificial brains.

00:38:46.120 --> 00:38:49.520
Since that time actually--
they began in 1997-- now

00:38:49.520 --> 00:38:52.910
they say they are running
between five and 10 years late.

00:38:52.910 --> 00:38:54.570
By still, they are
moving forward.

00:38:54.570 --> 00:38:57.810
They say between
2023 and 2028, they

00:38:57.810 --> 00:39:00.680
will be able to recreate
artificial brains

00:39:00.680 --> 00:39:03.080
equivalent to human brains.

00:39:03.080 --> 00:39:06.580
In the USA, as you
know, a few years ago

00:39:06.580 --> 00:39:08.640
the Human Connectome
project began.

00:39:08.640 --> 00:39:11.810
And last year,
President Barack Obama

00:39:11.810 --> 00:39:15.470
announced the Brain
Initiative, with $1 billion

00:39:15.470 --> 00:39:16.885
for the next 10 years.

00:39:18.080 --> 00:39:22.210
And just around the same
time, the European Union

00:39:22.210 --> 00:39:27.560
gave 1 billion euros for
the Human Brain Project.

00:39:27.560 --> 00:39:31.670
So I don't know if
the USA, if Europe,

00:39:31.670 --> 00:39:34.240
or Japan is going to do it.

00:39:34.240 --> 00:39:37.320
And China is coming up soon
with their own program.

00:39:37.320 --> 00:39:38.810
But in the next
10 years, we will

00:39:38.810 --> 00:39:40.440
understand how the
brain works and we

00:39:40.440 --> 00:39:43.850
will be able to replicate
artificial brains.

00:39:45.170 --> 00:39:49.270
So this is the second number I
would like for you to remember.

00:39:50.340 --> 00:39:52.250
And it's a very
simple schematic.

00:39:52.250 --> 00:39:57.360
But a brain basically
has 100 billion neurons.

00:39:57.360 --> 00:39:59.150
That is 10 to the 11 neurons.

00:39:59.150 --> 00:40:01.600
That is all the neurons
we have in the brain.

00:40:01.600 --> 00:40:02.820
We can have less.

00:40:02.820 --> 00:40:04.800
But we don't have more.

00:40:04.800 --> 00:40:06.720
So let's say 10 to the 11.

00:40:06.720 --> 00:40:10.990
Each neuron has about 1,000
connections, 2,000 connections,

00:40:10.990 --> 00:40:14.720
4,000 connections, maybe
a bit more, a bit less.

00:40:14.720 --> 00:40:18.140
That gives about 10 to the
14 connections or synapses.

00:40:18.140 --> 00:40:21.060
And those synapses are
the ones that compute.

00:40:21.060 --> 00:40:25.860
The brain has basically six
main frequencies, alpha waves,

00:40:25.860 --> 00:40:28.750
beta waves, delta
waves, mu waves,

00:40:28.750 --> 00:40:31.890
which are actually
very, very slow.

00:40:31.890 --> 00:40:37.485
The brain frequencies are 1
hertz, 10 hertz, 100 hertz.

00:40:37.485 --> 00:40:41.680
A very fast brain, like
Ray's brain, is 1 kilohertz.

00:40:43.130 --> 00:40:44.300
1 kilohertz.

00:40:44.300 --> 00:40:48.400
My telephone has
achieved of 3 gigahertz.

00:40:49.420 --> 00:40:53.630
So these telephone computes
a million times faster

00:40:53.630 --> 00:40:54.865
than any human brain.

00:40:56.050 --> 00:40:58.200
The difference obviously
is that I still

00:40:58.200 --> 00:41:02.010
have more neurons than
this has transistors.

00:41:02.010 --> 00:41:04.990
But this will change in
the next 10 to 20 years.

00:41:04.990 --> 00:41:09.830
And we will have devices that
process a million times faster

00:41:09.830 --> 00:41:14.300
than our brains and that have
as many transistors-equivalent

00:41:14.300 --> 00:41:15.480
neurons as we do.

00:41:15.480 --> 00:41:20.500
So the complexity of the human
software, to put it that way,

00:41:20.500 --> 00:41:22.020
is 10 to the 17.

00:41:22.020 --> 00:41:24.260
And this is a ballpark figure.

00:41:24.260 --> 00:41:27.190
Some people say it is 10
to the 15, 10 to the 16.

00:41:27.190 --> 00:41:29.890
Some people say it is 10
to the 18, 10 to the 20.

00:41:29.890 --> 00:41:31.440
I do not care.

00:41:31.440 --> 00:41:33.500
It is just a matter of time.

00:41:33.500 --> 00:41:36.530
Due to the law of
accelerating returns,

00:41:36.530 --> 00:41:39.500
it can be five years
earlier or five years later.

00:41:39.500 --> 00:41:41.890
But it is a finite number.

00:41:41.890 --> 00:41:42.530
That we know.

00:41:42.530 --> 00:41:44.540
It's a finite number.

00:41:44.540 --> 00:41:48.320
So if we don't talk about the
mind, the spirit, and the soul,

00:41:48.320 --> 00:41:52.780
then a brain just computes 10
to the 17 operations per second.

00:41:52.780 --> 00:41:56.155
And we are going to reach that
level in the next 20 years.

00:41:57.520 --> 00:41:59.430
But there are a
smaller brains too.

00:42:01.140 --> 00:42:02.731
No bigger brains yet.

00:42:02.731 --> 00:42:03.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:03.230 --> 00:42:05.320
But we can have smaller brains.

00:42:05.320 --> 00:42:08.660
And we are going to
connect the brains

00:42:08.660 --> 00:42:10.910
to computers and
to other devices,

00:42:10.910 --> 00:42:14.390
with internal brain implants or
with external brain implants.

00:42:16.300 --> 00:42:19.660
In fact, scientists
are beginning

00:42:19.660 --> 00:42:24.900
to do also brain-to-brain
interfaces.

00:42:24.900 --> 00:42:26.400
And they have been
able to transfer

00:42:26.400 --> 00:42:28.780
from the brain of a mouse to
the brain of another mouse,

00:42:28.780 --> 00:42:31.720
how to find cheese
in a labyrinth.

00:42:31.720 --> 00:42:33.240
This is just beginning.

00:42:33.240 --> 00:42:35.290
They are doing similar
experiments with monkeys.

00:42:36.570 --> 00:42:39.520
And then we are going to
do this also with humans.

00:42:39.520 --> 00:42:43.925
I have this technology,
which is already like three,

00:42:43.925 --> 00:42:44.550
four years ago.

00:42:44.550 --> 00:42:46.430
But I like it lot
because it lets

00:42:46.430 --> 00:42:49.950
you do a few experiments
in terms of concentration,

00:42:49.950 --> 00:42:54.290
meditation, targeting,
and playing other games.

00:42:54.290 --> 00:42:56.120
This basically is an
electroencephalogram.

00:42:56.992 --> 00:42:57.950
There is no magic here.

00:42:57.950 --> 00:42:59.570
This is an
electroencephalogram that

00:42:59.570 --> 00:43:03.450
reads what is happening in the
center part of my frontal lobe.

00:43:03.450 --> 00:43:06.360
And then through a
Bluetooth connection,

00:43:06.360 --> 00:43:10.820
sends it to my
computer and analyzes

00:43:10.820 --> 00:43:12.950
what is happening in my brain.

00:43:12.950 --> 00:43:17.636
Soon we will be able to do this
also from person to person.

00:43:17.636 --> 00:43:19.010
And with more
electrodes, we will

00:43:19.010 --> 00:43:20.770
be able to capture
more information.

00:43:20.770 --> 00:43:23.580
There are companies like
Emotiv that have 14 electrodes.

00:43:23.580 --> 00:43:25.670
Soon we would have
100 electrodes.

00:43:25.670 --> 00:43:27.630
Then we will have
1,000 electrodes.

00:43:27.630 --> 00:43:31.980
And then we want to stop using
this primitive technology

00:43:31.980 --> 00:43:33.570
called talking.

00:43:33.570 --> 00:43:35.930
Talking is a very
primitive technology,

00:43:35.930 --> 00:43:37.970
with a very narrow bandwidth.

00:43:37.970 --> 00:43:41.560
I have to say word
after word, after word.

00:43:41.560 --> 00:43:44.080
And you have to be listen
to me, word after word,

00:43:44.080 --> 00:43:48.240
after word, bad joke, another
word, and so on, and so forth.

00:43:48.240 --> 00:43:50.950
In the future, we
will be able to send

00:43:50.950 --> 00:43:54.150
the information from brain
to brain, like computers do.

00:43:55.570 --> 00:43:58.510
Everything I wanted to
say here is in my brain.

00:43:58.510 --> 00:44:01.540
But I cannot transfer it fast
enough because it is a narrow

00:44:01.540 --> 00:44:03.280
bandwidth communication system.

00:44:03.280 --> 00:44:06.890
Obviously, this was incredible,
because monkeys do not talk.

00:44:06.890 --> 00:44:09.800
So between a non-talking
monkey and us,

00:44:09.800 --> 00:44:11.710
there is a huge difference.

00:44:11.710 --> 00:44:15.320
But imagine when we have
brain to brain communication?

00:44:16.620 --> 00:44:17.720
It is not a dream.

00:44:17.720 --> 00:44:20.500
Telepathy we will have
thanks to technology.

00:44:20.500 --> 00:44:24.820
And we will do this
also with robots.

