Crisis has two
characters in Chinese.

00:51:39.780 --> 00:51:41.340
The first one means danger.

00:51:42.570 --> 00:51:45.220
But the second one means,
normally, opportunity.

00:51:46.350 --> 00:51:48.200
So we are going
through the biggest

00:51:48.200 --> 00:51:50.520
crisis in the
history of humanity.

00:51:50.520 --> 00:51:52.600
But let's not only
look at the danger.

00:51:52.600 --> 00:51:54.700
Let's look at the opportunity.

00:51:54.700 --> 00:51:56.436
Thank you very much.

00:51:56.436 --> 00:51:57.870
[APPLAUSE]

00:52:04.084 --> 00:52:07.500
AUDIENCE: A question
about-- it's sort

00:52:07.500 --> 00:52:08.820
of an ethical question.

00:52:08.820 --> 00:52:11.835
So you say there's going
to be these technologies.

00:52:13.210 --> 00:52:15.530
But technologies cost money.

00:52:15.530 --> 00:52:23.270
And I'm wondering do you see it
as being available to everyone

00:52:23.270 --> 00:52:27.270
or only the rich
people will become

00:52:27.270 --> 00:52:28.870
immortal and all these things?

00:52:28.870 --> 00:52:31.860
And then-- that's
basically the question.

00:52:31.860 --> 00:52:32.760
JOSE CORDEIRO: Yeah.

00:52:32.760 --> 00:52:34.590
The ethical issues
are fundamental.

00:52:35.680 --> 00:52:38.765
And I myself come from
the developing world.

00:52:40.520 --> 00:52:42.910
But I believe that
technology is actually

00:52:42.910 --> 00:52:46.820
what will help us to
leapfrog from poverty.

00:52:46.820 --> 00:52:49.760
If you look at the example
of mobile telephones,

00:52:49.760 --> 00:52:54.070
in Africa there were
no phones 20 years ago.

00:52:54.070 --> 00:52:57.360
Now, every African--
and I'm saying Africa

00:52:57.360 --> 00:53:00.330
because it is the poorest
continent in the planet-- has

00:53:00.330 --> 00:53:01.770
a mobile phone.

00:53:01.770 --> 00:53:02.570
Why?

00:53:02.570 --> 00:53:04.760
Because the first
technologies, when they come,

00:53:04.760 --> 00:53:07.920
actually they are expensive, and
they are for the rich people,

00:53:07.920 --> 00:53:09.290
and they do not work.

00:53:09.290 --> 00:53:10.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:10.290 --> 00:53:13.350
Then they go into
mass production.

00:53:13.350 --> 00:53:14.800
They become cheap.

00:53:14.800 --> 00:53:16.170
And they work.

00:53:16.170 --> 00:53:18.520
And this is when the
poor people get them.

00:53:18.520 --> 00:53:20.970
In terms of anti-aging
technologies,

00:53:20.970 --> 00:53:24.273
obviously the first
immortal-- to put it

00:53:24.273 --> 00:53:26.550
this way-- will be probably
people like Bill Gates

00:53:26.550 --> 00:53:28.210
or someone like that.

00:53:28.210 --> 00:53:30.920
But in a very short
time, everybody

00:53:30.920 --> 00:53:32.990
will have access to
those technologies.

00:53:32.990 --> 00:53:35.190
But I understand
the ethical issues.

00:53:35.190 --> 00:53:36.880
In fact, at
Singularity University,

00:53:36.880 --> 00:53:40.070
there is a special course
called Policy Law and Ethics,

00:53:40.070 --> 00:53:41.760
because this is fundamental.

00:53:41.760 --> 00:53:44.330
And I can tell you, as coming
from the developing world,

00:53:44.330 --> 00:53:45.940
I'm concerned about that.

00:53:45.940 --> 00:53:46.741
Yes?

00:53:46.741 --> 00:53:48.241
RAY KURTZWEIL: Only
the wealthy will

00:53:48.241 --> 00:53:52.142
access to these technologies at
a price where they don't work.

00:53:52.142 --> 00:53:54.760
By the time they work
well, like cellphones,

00:53:54.760 --> 00:53:56.617
we have today 1 to
2 billion of them.

00:53:56.617 --> 00:53:59.539
And we'll have 5 to 6
billion within a few years.

00:53:59.539 --> 00:54:00.831
And they get better and better.

00:54:00.831 --> 00:54:01.747
JOSE CORDEIRO: Um-huh.

00:54:01.747 --> 00:54:03.080
Yeah, those are smartphones.

00:54:03.080 --> 00:54:06.750
Because in terms of
cheap mobile phones,

00:54:06.750 --> 00:54:08.582
almost everybody
now could have one.

00:54:08.582 --> 00:54:10.790
AUDIENCE: As you know, we've
seen accelerating change

00:54:10.790 --> 00:54:12.920
in most technologies
in the world.

00:54:12.920 --> 00:54:14.870
Why do you think
that kind of change

00:54:14.870 --> 00:54:18.360
is not being seen in energy
and the use of fossil fuel?

00:54:19.314 --> 00:54:21.230
JOSE CORDEIRO: You know,
this is so beautiful.

00:54:22.380 --> 00:54:26.540
I actually went to give a talk
on that because that's my area.

00:54:26.540 --> 00:54:27.830
I work on energy.

00:54:27.830 --> 00:54:29.630
And people do not
see this coming.

00:54:29.630 --> 00:54:32.570
In the next 20
years, we are going

00:54:32.570 --> 00:54:36.800
to go through a solar
tsunami, a solar tsunami.

00:54:36.800 --> 00:54:38.790
What is happening
in solar energy

00:54:38.790 --> 00:54:42.260
is going to disrupt completely
the fossil fuel industry.

00:54:42.260 --> 00:54:43.760
And they don't see it,

00:54:43.760 --> 00:54:46.230
I was talking to
Vinod Khosla, one

00:54:46.230 --> 00:54:48.130
of the co-founders
of Sun Microsystems.

00:54:48.130 --> 00:54:51.430
And he said the same happened
30 years ago when they did not

00:54:51.430 --> 00:54:53.480
see the mobile
phones, especially

00:54:53.480 --> 00:54:55.860
people in the normal
telephone companies.

00:54:55.860 --> 00:54:58.080
And now, everybody has
come a mobile phone.

00:54:58.080 --> 00:55:01.500
What we are going to see in
solar energy and renewables

00:55:01.500 --> 00:55:02.460
is incredible.

00:55:02.460 --> 00:55:06.550
And this year is very especially
important because now we

00:55:06.550 --> 00:55:09.030
have reached what is
called grid parity,

00:55:09.030 --> 00:55:12.540
when renewables are
cheaper than fossil fuels.

00:55:12.540 --> 00:55:15.210
And the trend continues cheaper
and cheaper and cheaper.

00:55:15.210 --> 00:55:19.230
And now, there is mass
production of solar panels.

00:55:19.230 --> 00:55:21.730
And solar panels use many
of the same technologies

00:55:21.730 --> 00:55:24.920
as chips, semiconductor
chips, made

00:55:24.920 --> 00:55:27.150
of silicon and
many other things.

00:55:27.150 --> 00:55:29.570
Companies like Applied
Materials-- Applied Materials

00:55:29.570 --> 00:55:33.830
made chips for computers
and chips for solar panels

00:55:33.830 --> 00:55:36.660
We are going to see
a radical change.

00:55:36.660 --> 00:55:40.340
And, in fact, Ray says-- and
also I believe in it strongly--

00:55:40.340 --> 00:55:45.040
in 20 years, it will be
fully reliable, mostly solar.

00:55:45.040 --> 00:55:47.240
RAY KURTZWEIL: Larry
Page and I did a study

00:55:47.240 --> 00:55:50.910
for the National Academy of
Engineering a few years ago,

00:55:50.910 --> 00:55:52.170
before he got this new job.

00:55:53.430 --> 00:55:58.165
And we noted a exponential
growth in the number of watts

00:55:58.165 --> 00:56:00.308
for this plateau has
been doubling every two

00:56:00.308 --> 00:56:02.643
years, for the last 30 years.

00:56:02.643 --> 00:56:05.933
It's now only five doublings,
and two years each,

00:56:05.933 --> 00:56:08.188
from 100% of the world's energy.

00:56:08.188 --> 00:56:11.441
At which point, we'll be
using [INAUDIBLE] sunlight

00:56:11.441 --> 00:56:11.940
[INAUDIBLE].

00:56:13.330 --> 00:56:14.470
JOSE CORDEIRO: Absolutely.

00:56:14.470 --> 00:56:15.660
This is so true.

00:56:15.660 --> 00:56:19.210
We receive 10,000
times more solar energy

00:56:19.210 --> 00:56:20.840
on the atmosphere of
the planet than we

00:56:20.840 --> 00:56:23.010
consume-- 10,000 times more.

00:56:23.010 --> 00:56:24.720
We just need 1% of 1%.

00:56:25.790 --> 00:56:28.750
And this is growing really
exponentially, as Ray said.

00:56:28.750 --> 00:56:30.590
And it's doubling
every two years.

00:56:30.590 --> 00:56:36.450
So I do believe in 20 years,
fossil fuel will be fossil.

00:56:36.450 --> 00:56:39.220
AUDIENCE: We're working on
sequencing the human genome,

00:56:39.220 --> 00:56:40.530
understanding the human brain.

00:56:40.530 --> 00:56:42.582
How we're doing all the
commensal organisms that

00:56:42.582 --> 00:56:44.540
make up the walking
ecosystems that we actually

00:56:44.540 --> 00:56:47.900
are, since our human cells
are outnumbered drastically

00:56:47.900 --> 00:56:51.040
by all of the microflora
and fauna in our bodies?

00:56:52.309 --> 00:56:53.100
JOSE CORDEIRO: Yes.

00:56:53.100 --> 00:56:55.950
There are also many
people working on that.

00:56:55.950 --> 00:56:58.010
As you said, we have
more foreign cells,

00:56:58.010 --> 00:57:01.260
or non-human cells, than
human cells in our bodies.

00:57:01.260 --> 00:57:04.100
But I don't particularly
think that that is a problem.

00:57:04.100 --> 00:57:07.310
Because in order to
create artificial organs,

00:57:07.310 --> 00:57:10.460
we don't have to go through
all the same messy procedures

00:57:10.460 --> 00:57:12.760
that have created
us or that made us.

00:57:13.890 --> 00:57:16.480
Like if you want to do
an artificial heart,

00:57:16.480 --> 00:57:18.620
you don't copy a natural
heart completely.

00:57:19.690 --> 00:57:23.250
Or if you create a plane,
you don't copy a bird.

00:57:23.250 --> 00:57:25.970
So I think many of the things
we will do in the future

00:57:25.970 --> 00:57:29.470
will not be totally biological
and will not necessarily

00:57:29.470 --> 00:57:30.710
follow biology.

00:57:30.710 --> 00:57:32.655
But anyway, that's not
my area of expertise.

00:57:34.530 --> 00:57:36.950
AUDIENCE: When we see
the death of death,

00:57:36.950 --> 00:57:38.700
will we also see
the death of birth?

00:57:40.115 --> 00:57:41.115
AUDIENCE: Good question.

00:57:43.050 --> 00:57:44.800
JOSE CORDEIRO: Well,
actually it might

00:57:44.800 --> 00:57:47.260
happen because in fact the
population of the planet

00:57:47.260 --> 00:57:48.850
is already stabilizing.

00:57:48.850 --> 00:57:51.700
Today, we are over
7 billion people.

00:57:51.700 --> 00:57:55.190
And in most developed countries,
except for the USA, and Canada,

00:57:55.190 --> 00:57:57.340
and Australia, the
developed countries

00:57:57.340 --> 00:57:59.242
have stabilized
or are going down.

00:57:59.242 --> 00:58:00.450
I lived three years in Japan.

00:58:00.450 --> 00:58:03.610
The population of Japan
declined 1 million people

00:58:03.610 --> 00:58:06.080
in the three years
I was in Japan.

00:58:06.080 --> 00:58:09.410
Russia is going through
a collapse in population.

00:58:09.410 --> 00:58:13.840
China will see the most
incredible common suicide.

00:58:14.970 --> 00:58:19.815
China is going to lose 200
million people between 2030

00:58:19.815 --> 00:58:21.180
and 2050.

00:58:21.180 --> 00:58:24.520
In any event, we are reaching
stabilization of population.

00:58:25.590 --> 00:58:28.520
And what will happen in
the future, I do not know.

00:58:28.520 --> 00:58:31.380
But we are beginning to
colonize the universe as well.

00:58:31.380 --> 00:58:33.080
We need more people
to go to Mars.

00:58:33.080 --> 00:58:34.027
We need volunteers.

00:58:34.027 --> 00:58:35.110
Do you want to go to Mars?

00:58:36.700 --> 00:58:39.500
Even if it is one
way, as-- Elon Musk,

00:58:39.500 --> 00:58:44.380
Elon Musk said he wants to die
on Mars, but not on landing.

00:58:44.380 --> 00:58:45.808
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:48.734 --> 00:58:51.150
AUDIENCE: Kind of piggy-backing
off this question as well,

00:58:51.150 --> 00:58:54.150
but assuming that we see at
least a slowdown in birth

00:58:54.150 --> 00:58:55.770
rates, how would
that affect-- I mean

00:58:55.770 --> 00:58:58.900
you saw how small a portion of
the whole evolutionary process

00:58:58.900 --> 00:58:59.659
we are.

00:58:59.659 --> 00:59:01.200
Would we just be
drawing a line there

00:59:01.200 --> 00:59:03.240
And we'd have to manually tinker
with ourselves from then on?

00:59:03.240 --> 00:59:05.830
Or like how do we continue to
evolve as a species as well?

00:59:05.830 --> 00:59:07.820
Because I feel like we're
not exactly perfect.

00:59:09.247 --> 00:59:10.080
JOSE CORDEIRO: Yeah.

00:59:10.080 --> 00:59:10.621
I don't know.

00:59:10.621 --> 00:59:13.150
Maybe Ray would like to
comment on that better than me.

00:59:13.150 --> 00:59:14.900
But I think we are
going to see a Cambrian

00:59:14.900 --> 00:59:16.390
explosion of new life forms.

00:59:16.671 --> 00:59:18.670
RAY KURTZWEIL: Well, it
was actually surprising.

00:59:19.860 --> 00:59:23.080
Scientists discovered that there
has been biological evolution

00:59:23.080 --> 00:59:25.540
in humans in the
last thousand years.

00:59:25.540 --> 00:59:28.180
But nonetheless,
it's insignificant

00:59:28.180 --> 00:59:30.635
compared to our
technological evolution.

00:59:30.635 --> 00:59:33.090
And that is expanding
exponentially.

00:59:33.090 --> 00:59:35.660
And we're going to-- we are
enhancing ourselves already.

00:59:35.660 --> 00:59:37.432
The kid who helped to
build the smartphone

00:59:37.432 --> 00:59:40.285
has access to more
information than the president

00:59:40.285 --> 00:59:43.060
of the United States
had 15 years ago.

00:59:43.060 --> 00:59:45.810
And we're get closer and
closer to these technologies.

00:59:45.810 --> 00:59:48.750
And that's the future
evolution of humanity,

00:59:48.750 --> 00:59:51.200
into a human-technological
symbiosis.

00:59:53.670 --> 00:59:54.920
JOSE CORDEIRO: Oh, here, here.

00:59:56.546 --> 00:59:58.420
AUDIENCE: Is the timing
of these technologies

00:59:58.420 --> 00:59:59.795
being planned at
all in the sense

00:59:59.795 --> 01:00:01.540
that if we're going
to become immortal,

01:00:01.540 --> 01:00:03.789
then maybe we should have
figured out all our resource

01:00:03.789 --> 01:00:05.930
problems before then or
we should have figured out

01:00:05.930 --> 01:00:07.770
a way off this planet
before that point?

01:00:07.770 --> 01:00:10.145
Otherwise, we're going to
choke ourselves on this planet.

01:00:10.445 --> 01:00:11.820
JOSE CORDEIRO:
Actually, we think

01:00:11.820 --> 01:00:14.550
we have unlimited
resources on this planet.

01:00:14.550 --> 01:00:18.090
Do you know how much are
you worth on raw material?

01:00:18.090 --> 01:00:21.210
You're not worth even $100.

01:00:21.210 --> 01:00:23.120
Or me-- don't take
it personally.

01:00:23.120 --> 01:00:24.110
[LAUGHTER]

01:00:24.110 --> 01:00:26.780
I mean we are 70% water.

01:00:26.780 --> 01:00:30.360
And we are not Evian
or Perrier water.

01:00:30.360 --> 01:00:32.000
We are tap water.

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:36.000
The other 30% that makes us
are very simple elements.

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:38.347
So they are calcium
and potassium.

01:00:38.347 --> 01:00:39.430
We are very cheap to make.

01:00:39.430 --> 01:00:43.190
We are so cheap to make that our
parents made us in one night.

01:00:44.300 --> 01:00:46.530
So humans are very
cheap to make.

01:00:46.530 --> 01:00:50.190
Now with nanotechnology, we
will be able to structure

01:00:50.190 --> 01:00:52.120
matter the way we want it.

01:00:52.120 --> 01:00:55.070
So actually I think we
have enough resources

01:00:55.070 --> 01:00:56.790
on this planet.

01:00:56.790 --> 01:01:00.630
We don't have a resource
scarcity problem.

01:01:00.630 --> 01:01:03.880
And the game with
nanotechnology will radically

01:01:03.880 --> 01:01:06.070
change many things.

01:01:06.070 --> 01:01:08.650
And the universe is
full of mass anyway.

01:01:08.650 --> 01:01:13.190
I mean we live in a tiny, tiny
planet, in a tiny solar system,

01:01:13.190 --> 01:01:14.330
in a tiny galaxy.

01:01:15.640 --> 01:01:19.405
I mean the universe is so big,
so huge, so full of resources.

01:01:20.410 --> 01:01:22.217
And we are not even $100.

01:01:22.217 --> 01:01:24.800
AUDIENCE: So when you speak of
these accelerating technologies

01:01:24.800 --> 01:01:27.060
and nanotechnology,
obviously there

01:01:27.060 --> 01:01:30.480
is incredible opportunity for
transhumanistic possibilities,

01:01:30.480 --> 01:01:32.426
for things to go really well.

01:01:32.426 --> 01:01:35.235
But when you speak of, I
guess, developing emotions

01:01:35.235 --> 01:01:37.360
in robots and those sort
of artificial intelligence

01:01:37.360 --> 01:01:39.070
systems, and I
think there's also

01:01:39.070 --> 01:01:41.240
a possibility for
negative almost

01:01:41.240 --> 01:01:42.920
volition of these systems.

01:01:42.920 --> 01:01:45.337
Are you worried about that,
I guess in the future?

01:01:45.337 --> 01:01:47.670
JOSE CORDEIRO: Of course, I'm
always worried about this.

01:01:47.670 --> 01:01:49.950
But also I wanted to
emphasize different cultures.

01:01:49.950 --> 01:01:53.497
That's why I said in Japan,
the Japanese love robots.

01:01:53.497 --> 01:01:55.205
I mean they want to
have sex with robots.

01:01:56.770 --> 01:02:00.090
They will probably do it
even better sometimes, huh?

01:02:00.090 --> 01:02:02.280
Or they will not get tired.

01:02:02.280 --> 01:02:03.750
But I am concerned, obviously.

01:02:03.750 --> 01:02:04.960
I am concerned.

01:02:04.960 --> 01:02:08.787
This is the Terminator
scenario or the Skynet.

01:02:08.787 --> 01:02:10.370
Does anyone know
Google is the Skynet?

01:02:12.740 --> 01:02:14.700
So this is a possibility.

01:02:14.700 --> 01:02:18.080
But I think evolution has been
improving the human conditions

01:02:18.080 --> 01:02:20.260
throughout the ages
and we will continue.

01:02:20.260 --> 01:02:23.600
But it is true technology can
be used for good or bad things,

01:02:23.600 --> 01:02:24.510
beginning with fire.

01:02:24.510 --> 01:02:26.920
Fire was one of the first
inventions by humans

01:02:26.920 --> 01:02:28.120
half a million years ago.

01:02:28.120 --> 01:02:31.430
And fire, you can use it
for cooking or getting warm,

01:02:31.430 --> 01:02:33.190
or for burning your enemy.

01:02:33.190 --> 01:02:35.492
Or nuclear technology,
for electricity

01:02:35.492 --> 01:02:36.450
or for nuclear weapons?

01:02:36.450 --> 01:02:39.050
So technology has a dark side.

01:02:39.050 --> 01:02:42.090
But I think the positive
side is much bigger.

01:02:42.090 --> 01:02:44.820
And humanity, obviously,
in general, is good.

01:02:44.820 --> 01:02:47.020
I believe most humans are good.

01:02:47.289 --> 01:02:48.830
RAY KURTZWEIL: I
just wanted to thank

01:02:48.830 --> 01:02:51.960
you, Jose, for an
inspiring presentation.

01:02:51.960 --> 01:02:52.700
Thank you.

01:02:52.700 --> 01:02:53.900
JOSE CORDEIRO: Thank you.

01:02:53.900 --> 01:02:55.750
[APPLAUSE]

